# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biointensive-agriculture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamics has much in common with other organic approaches – it emphasizes the use of manures and composts and excludes the use of synthetic (artificial) fertilizers, pesticides and herbicides on soil and plants.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Methods unique to the biodynamic approach include its treatment of animals, crops, and soil as a single system, an emphasis from its beginnings on local production and distribution systems, its use of traditional and development of new local breeds and varieties.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Some methods use an astrological sowing and planting calendar.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] No difference in beneficial outcomes has been scientifically established between certified biodynamic agricultural techniques and similar organic and integrated farming practices.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamic agriculture is a pseudoscience as it lacks scientific evidence for its efficacy because of its reliance upon esoteric and mystical beliefs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] As of 2022, biodynamic techniques were used on 255,051 hectares in 65 countries, led by Germany, Italy and France.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Germany accounts for 42% of the global total.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The remainder average 1,750 ha per country.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamic methods of cultivating grapevines have been taken up by several notable vineyards.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] There are certification agencies for biodynamic products, most of which are members of the international biodynamics standards group Demeter International.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamics was the first modern organic agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Its development began in 1924 with a series of eight lectures on agriculture given by philosopher Rudolf Steiner at Schloss Koberwitz in Silesia, Germany (now Kobierzyce in Poland).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] These lectures, the first known presentation of organic agriculture, were held in response to a request by farmers who noticed degraded soil conditions and a deterioration in the health and quality of crops and livestock resulting from the use of chemical fertilizers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The 111 attendees, fewer than half of whom were farmers, came from six countries, primarily Germany and Poland.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The lectures were published in November 1924; the first English translation appeared in 1928 as *The Agriculture Course*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Steiner emphasized that the methods he proposed should be tested experimentally.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] For this purpose, Steiner established a research group, the "Agricultural Experimental Circle of Anthroposophical Farmers and Gardeners of the General Anthroposophical Society".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Between 1924 and 1939, this research group attracted about 800 members from around the world, including Europe, the Americas and Australasia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Bartsch was also instrumental in developing a sales organisation for biodynamic products, Demeter, which still exists today.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The Research Association was renamed the Imperial Association for Biodynamic Agriculture (*Reichsverband für biologisch-dynamische Wirtschaftsweise*) in 1933.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] It was dissolved by the National Socialist regime in 1941.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In 1931 the association had 250 members in Germany, 109 in Switzerland, 104 in other European countries and 24 outside Europe.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The oldest biodynamic farms are the Wurzerhof in Austria and Marienhöhe in Germany.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In 1938, Ehrenfried Pfeiffer's text, *Bio-Dynamic Farming and Gardening*, was published in five languages – English, Dutch, Italian, French, and German; this became the standard work in the field for several decades.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The following year Pfeiffer's book was published in Danish by Carl Vett.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In July 1939, at the invitation of Walter James, 4th Baron Northbourne, Pfeiffer travelled to the UK and presented the Betteshanger Summer School and Conference on Biodynamic Farming at Northbourne's farm in Kent.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In the 1950s, Hans Mueller was encouraged by Steiner's work to create the organic-biological farming method in Switzerland; this later developed to become the largest certifier of organic products in Europe, *Bioland*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Today biodynamics is practised in more than 50 countries worldwide and in a variety of circumstances, ranging from temperate arable farming, viticulture in France, cotton production in Egypt, to silkworm breeding in China.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Demeter International is the primary certification agency for farms and gardens using the methods.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In 2020 Demeter International and the International Biodynamic Association joined to become the Biodynamic Federation – Demeter International.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In common with other forms of organic agriculture, biodynamic agriculture uses management practices that are intended to "restore, maintain and enhance ecological harmony".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Central features include crop diversification, the avoidance of chemical soil treatments and off-farm inputs generally, decentralized production and distribution, and the consideration of celestial and terrestrial influences on biological organisms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The Demeter Association recommends that "(a) minimum of ten percent of the total farm acreage be set aside as a biodiversity preserve.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] That may include but is not limited to forests, wetlands, riparian corridors, and intentionally planted insectaries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Diversity in crop rotation and perennial planting is required: no annual crop can be planted in the same field for more than two years in succession.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The Demeter Association also recommends that the individual design of the land "by the farmer, as determined by site conditions, is one of the basic tenets of biodynamic agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The prime objective is always to encourage healthy conditions for life": soil fertility, plant and animal health, and product quality.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] "Disease and insect control are addressed through botanical species diversity, predator habitat, balanced crop nutrition, and attention to light penetration and airflow.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamic agriculture differs from many forms of organic agriculture in its spiritual, mystical, and astrological orientation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] It shares a spiritual focus, as well as its view toward improving humanity, with the "nature farming" movement in Japan.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Important features include the use of livestock manures to sustain plant growth (recycling of nutrients), maintenance and improvement of soil quality, and the health and well-being of crops and animals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Cover crops, green manures and crop rotations are used extensively and the farms to foster the diversity of plant and animal life, and to enhance the biological cycles and the biological activity of the soil.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamic farms often have a cultural component and encourage local community, both through developing local sales and through on-farm community building activities.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Some biodynamic farms use the Community Supported Agriculture model, which has connections with social threefolding.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In his "agricultural course" Steiner prescribed nine different preparations to aid fertilisation, and described how these were to be prepared.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Steiner believed that these preparations mediated terrestrial and cosmic forces into the soil.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The prepared substances are numbered 500 through 508, where the first two are used for preparing fields, and the other seven are used for making compost.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] A long term trial (DOK experiment) evaluating the biodynamic farming system in comparison with organic and conventional farming systems, found that both organic farming and biodynamic farming resulted in enhanced soil properties, but had lower yields than conventional farming.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Although the preparations have direct nutrient values, modern biodynamic practitioners believe their benefit is to support the self-regulating capacities of the biota already present in the soil and compost.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Critics of the practice have pointed out that no evidence or logic underlies the practices themselves, which instead are dependent on magical thinking and debunked theories of Steiner himself.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] There is no evidence that biodynamic practices have any benefit beyond the direct nutrients they add as fertilizer, which may itself be of smaller benefit than other traditionally organic or commercial fertilizers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The compost preparations Steiner recommended employ herbs which are frequently used in alternative medical remedies.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Many of the same herbs Steiner referenced are used in organic practices to make foliar fertilizers, green manure, or in composting.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] This aspect of biodynamics has been termed "astrological" and "pseudoscientific" in nature.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamic agriculture has focused on the open pollination of seeds (with farmers thereby generally growing their own seed) and the development of locally adapted varieties.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The Demeter biodynamic certification system established in 1924 was the first certification and labelling system for organic production.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] As of 2018, to receive certification as biodynamic, the farm must meet the following standards: agronomic guidelines, greenhouse management, structural components, livestock guidelines, and post-harvest handling and processing procedures.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The term *Biodynamic* is a trademark held by the Demeter association of biodynamic farmers for the purpose of maintaining production standards used both in farming and processing foodstuffs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The trademark is intended to protect both the consumer and the producers of biodynamic produce.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Demeter International an organization of member countries; each country has its own Demeter organization which is required to meet international production standards (but can also exceed them).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The original Demeter organization was founded in 1928; the U.S.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Demeter Association was formed in the 1980s and certified its first farm in 1982.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In France, Biodyvin certifies biodynamic wine.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In Egypt, SEKEM has created the Egyptian Biodynamic Association (EBDA), an association that provides training for farmers to become certified.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] As of 2006, more than 200 wineries worldwide were certified as biodynamic; numerous other wineries employ biodynamic methods to a greater or lesser extent.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Research into biodynamic farming has been complicated by the difficulty of isolating the distinctively biodynamic aspects when conducting comparative trials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Consequently, there is no strong body of material that provides evidence of any specific effect.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Since biodynamic farming is a form of organic farming, it can be generally assumed to share its characteristics, including "less stressed soils and thus diverse and highly interrelated soil communities".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Both factors were similar to the result in organically cultivated fields.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In a 2002 newspaper editorial, Peter Treue, agricultural researcher at the University of Kiel, characterized biodynamics as pseudoscience and argued that similar or equal results can be obtained using standard organic farming principles.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] He wrote that some biodynamic preparations more resemble alchemy or magic akin to geomancy.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In a 1994 analysis, Holger Kirchmann, a soil researcher with the Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, concluded that Steiner's instructions were occult and dogmatic, and cannot contribute to the development of alternative or sustainable agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] According to Kirchmann, many of Steiner's statements are not provable because scientifically clear hypotheses cannot be made from his descriptions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Kirchmann asserted that when methods of biodynamic agriculture were tested scientifically, the results were unconvincing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Based on the scant scientific testing of biodynamics, Chalker-Scott concluded "no evidence exists" that homeopathic preparations improve the soil.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] In Michael Shermer's *The Skeptic Encyclopedia of Pseudoscience*, Dan Dugan says that the way biodynamic preparations are supposed to be implemented are formulated solely on the basis of Steiner's "own insight".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Skeptic Brian Dunning writes "the best way to think of 'biodynamic agriculture' would be as a magic spell cast over an entire farm.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Biodynamic farmers are "charged with developing a continuous dialogue between biodynamic science and the natural sciences *sensu stricto*", despite important differences in paradigms, world views, and value systems.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Steiner's theory was similar to those of the agricultural scientist Richard Krzymowski, who was teaching in Breslau since 1922.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Rauch mentioned in 1995, concerning the reprint of a book from Raoul Heinrich Francé, another source probably used by Steiner.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] According to a scientific paper of Holger Kirchmann in 2021, the auras and forces mentioned by Steiner are not known to science.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] His statement (hypothesis) of "living forces" affecting crops cannot be tested, and is thus not falsifiable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] However, when a hypothesis is not falsifiable, this is a sign of pseudoscience.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] A research team from the Botanical Garden and Department of Experimental and Social Sciences Education of the Faculty of Teacher Training of the University of Valencia warned in 2021 about the risk of pseudoscience in relation with myths or beliefs about the influence of the moon on agriculture.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] The findings of this scientific review of over 100 papers (including scientific articles, papers and higher education textbooks) have been published in the journal *Agronomy*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] They found that there is no reliable, science-based evidence for any relationship between lunar phases and plant physiology in any plant–science related textbooks or peer-reviewed journal articles justifying agricultural practices conditioned by the Moon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Nor does evidence from the field of physics support a causal relationship between lunar forces and plant responses.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biodynamic-agriculture] Therefore, popular agricultural practices that are tied to lunar phases have no scientific backing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] Many of the techniques that contribute to the biointensive method were present in the agriculture of the ancient Chinese, Greeks, Mayans, and of the Early Modern period in Europe, as well as in West Africa (Tapades of Fouta Djallon) from at least the late 18th century.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] Sustainable bio-intensive farming (BIF) system, which emphasizes biodiversity conservation; recycling of nutrients; synergy among crops, animals, soils, and other biological components; and regeneration and conservation of resources is a type of agro-ecological approach.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] This alternative approach can appropriately address the central issue of hunger, poverty, food / nutrition insecurity and livelihoods (Rajbhandari, 1999).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] Ecology Action's research (Jeavons, J.C., 2001.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] *Biointensive Mini-Farming* Journal of Sustainable Agriculture (Vol.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] The biointensive method typically concentrates on the vegan diet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] This does not mean that biointensive farming must exclude the raising of animals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] Animals, while not considered by biointensive practitioners to be sustainable, can be incorporated into biointensive systems, although they increase the amount of land and labor required considerably.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/biointensive-agriculture] The article goes on to estimate the square footage required to grow fodder for various animals (and compost to replenish the soil), and provides a discussion on whether animal manure should be used as a fertilizer/compost supplement.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille is named after its creator, Louis Braille, a Frenchman who lost his sight as a result of a childhood accident.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1824, at the age of fifteen, he developed the braille code based on the French alphabet as an improvement on night writing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] He published his system, which subsequently included musical notation, in 1829.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The second revision, published in 1837, was the first binary form of writing developed in the modern era.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille characters are formed using a combination of six raised dots arranged in a 3 × 2 matrix, called the braille cell.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The number and arrangement of these dots distinguishes one character from another.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In addition to braille text (letters, punctuation, contractions), it is also possible to create embossed illustrations and graphs, with the lines either solid or made of series of dots, arrows, and bullets that are larger than braille dots.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A full braille cell includes six raised dots arranged in two columns, each column having three dots.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The dot positions are identified by numbers from one to six.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] There are 64 possible combinations, including no dots at all for a word space.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Dot configurations can be used to represent a letter, digit, punctuation mark, or even a word.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Early braille education is crucial to literacy, education and employment among the blind.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Despite the evolution of new technologies, including screen reader software that reads information aloud, braille provides blind people with access to spelling, punctuation and other aspects of written language less accessible through audio alone.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] While some have suggested that audio-based technologies will decrease the need for braille, technological advancements such as braille displays have continued to make braille more accessible and available.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille users highlight that braille remains as essential as print is to the sighted.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille was based on a tactile code, now known as night writing, developed by Charles Barbier.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille identified three major defects of the code: first, the symbols represented phonetic sounds and not letters of the alphabet – thus the code was unable to render the orthography of the words.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Second, the 12-dot symbols could not easily fit beneath the pad of the reading finger.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] This required the reading finger to move in order to perceive the whole symbol, which slowed the reading process.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] (This was because Barbier's system was based only on the number of dots in each of two 6-dot columns, not the pattern of the dots.) Third, the code did not include symbols for numerals or punctuation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille's solution was to use 6-dot cells and to assign a specific pattern to each letter of the alphabet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille also developed symbols for representing numerals and punctuation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] At first, braille was a one-to-one transliteration of the French alphabet, but soon various abbreviations (contractions) and even logograms were developed, creating a system much more like shorthand.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Today, there are braille codes for over 133 languages.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In English, some variations in the braille codes have traditionally existed among English-speaking countries.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1991, work to standardize the braille codes used in the English-speaking world began.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Unified English Braille (UEB) has been adopted in all seven member countries of the International Council on English Braille (ICEB) as well as Nigeria.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille is derived from the Latin alphabet, albeit indirectly.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In Braille's original system, the dot patterns were assigned to letters according to their position within the alphabetic order of the French alphabet of the time, with accented letters and *w* sorted at the end.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Unlike print, which consists of mostly arbitrary symbols, the braille alphabet follows a logical sequence.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The first ten letters of the alphabet, *a*–*j*, use the upper four dot positions: ⠁⠃⠉⠙⠑⠋⠛⠓⠊⠚ (filled circles in the table below).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] These stand for the ten digits *1*–*9* and *0* in an alphabetic numeral system similar to Greek numerals (as well as derivations of it, including Hebrew numerals, Cyrillic numerals, Abjad numerals, also Hebrew gematria and Greek isopsephy).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Though the dots are assigned in no obvious order, the cells with the fewest dots are assigned to the first three letters (and lowest digits), *abc* = *123* (⠁⠃⠉), and to the three vowels in this part of the alphabet, *aei* (⠁⠑⠊), whereas the even digits *4*, *6*, *8*, *0* (⠙⠋⠓⠚) are right angles.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The next ten letters (the next "decade") are the same again, but with dots also at both position 3 and position 6 (green dots in the bottom rows of the cells in the table above).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Here *w* was left out as it was not part of the official French alphabet in Braille's time; the French order of the decade was *u v x y z ç é à è ù* (⠥⠧⠭⠽⠵⠯⠿⠷⠮⠾).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The next ten letters, ending in *w*, are the same again, except that for this series position 6 (purple dot in the bottom right corner of the cell in the table above) is used without a dot at position 3.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In French braille these are the letters *â ê î ô û ë ï ü œ w* (⠡⠣⠩⠹⠱⠫⠻⠳⠪⠺).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] *W* had been tacked onto the end of 39 letters of the French alphabet to accommodate English.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The *a*–*j* series shifted down by one dot space (⠂⠆⠒⠲⠢⠖⠶⠦⠔⠴) is used for punctuation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Letters *a* ⠁ and *c* ⠉, which only use dots in the top row, were shifted two places for the apostrophe and hyphen: ⠄⠤.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The first four decades are similar in that the numeric sequence is extended by adding the decade dots, whereas in the fifth decade it is extended by shifting it downward.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The fifth through ninth used dashes as well as dots, but they proved to be impractical to distinguish by touch under normal conditions and were soon abandoned.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] From the beginning, these additional decades could be substituted with what we now know as the number sign (⠼) applied to the earlier decades, though that only caught on for the digits (the old 5th decade being replaced by ⠼ applied to the 1st decade).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The dash occupying the top row of the original sixth decade was simply omitted, producing the modern fifth decade.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Under international consensus, most braille alphabets follow the French sorting order for the 26 letters of the basic Latin alphabet, and there have been attempts at unifying the letters beyond these 26 (see international braille), though differences remain, for example, in German Braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A convention sometimes seen for letters beyond the basic 26 is to exploit the physical symmetry of braille patterns iconically, for example, by assigning a reversed *n* to *ñ* or an inverted *s* to *sh*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A third principle was to assign braille codes according to frequency, with the simplest patterns (quickest ones to write with a stylus) assigned to the most frequent letters of the alphabet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Finally, there are braille scripts that do not order the codes numerically at all, such as Japanese Braille and Korean Braille, which are based on more abstract principles of syllable composition.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Texts are sometimes written in a script of eight dots per cell rather than six, enabling them to encode a greater number of symbols.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] (See Gardner–Salinas braille codes.) Luxembourgish Braille has adopted eight-dot cells for general use; for example, accented letters take the unaccented versions plus dot 8.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille was the first writing system with binary encoding.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The physical representation of those six-bit characters with raised dots in a braille cell.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Within an individual cell, the dot positions are arranged in two columns of three positions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A raised dot can appear in any of the six positions, producing 64 (26) possible patterns, including one in which there are no raised dots.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For reference purposes, a pattern is commonly described by listing the positions where dots are raised, the positions being universally numbered, from top to bottom, as 1 to 3 on the left and 4 to 6 on the right.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, dot pattern 1-3-4 describes a cell with three dots raised, at the top and bottom in the left column and at the top of the right column: that is, the letter ⠍ *m*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The lines of horizontal braille text are separated by a space, much like visible printed text, so that the dots of one line can be differentiated from the braille text above and below.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Different assignments of braille codes (or code pages) are used to map the character sets of different printed scripts to the six-bit cells.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille assignments have also been created for mathematical and musical notation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] However, because the six-dot braille cell allows only 64 (26) patterns, including space, the characters of a braille script commonly have multiple values, depending on their context.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] That is, character mapping between print and braille is not one-to-one.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, the character ⠙ corresponds in print to both the letter *d* and the digit *4*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In addition to simple encoding, many braille alphabets use contractions to reduce the size of braille texts and to increase reading speed.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille may be produced by hand using a slate and stylus in which each dot is created from the back of the page, writing in mirror image, or it may be produced on a braille typewriter or Perkins Brailler, or an electronic Brailler or braille notetaker.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille users with access to smartphones may also activate the on-screen braille input keyboard, to type braille symbols on to their device by placing their fingers on to the screen according to the dot configuration of the symbols they wish to form.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] These symbols are automatically translated into print on the screen.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The different tools that exist for writing braille allow the braille user to select the method that is best for a given task.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, the slate and stylus is a portable writing tool, much like the pen and paper for the sighted.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Errors can be erased using a braille eraser or can be overwritten with all six dots (⠿).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] *Interpoint* refers to braille printing that is offset, so that the paper can be embossed on both sides, with the dots on one side appearing between the divots that form the dots on the other.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Using a computer or other electronic device, Braille may be produced with a braille embosser (printer) or a refreshable braille display (screen).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille has been extended to an 8-dot code, particularly for use with braille embossers and refreshable braille displays.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 8-dot braille the additional dots are added at the bottom of the cell, giving a matrix 4 dots high by 2 dots wide.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The additional dots are given the numbers 7 (for the lower-left dot) and 8 (for the lower-right dot).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Eight-dot braille has the advantages that the casing of each letter is coded in the cell and that every printable ASCII character can be encoded in a single cell.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] All 256 (28) possible combinations of 8 dots are encoded by the Unicode standard.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille with six dots is frequently stored as Braille ASCII.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The first 25 braille letters, up through the first half of the 3rd decade, transcribe *a–z* (skipping *w*).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In English Braille, the rest of that decade is rounded out with the ligatures *and, for, of, the,* and *with*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Omitting dot 3 from these forms the 4th decade, the ligatures *ch, gh, sh, th, wh, ed, er, ou, ow* and the letter *w*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Various formatting marks affect the values of the letters that follow them.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] They have no direct equivalent in print.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] That is, ⠠⠁ is read as capital 'A', and ⠼⠁ as the digit '1'.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] ⠦ is both the question mark and the opening quotation mark.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Its reading depends on whether it occurs before a word or after.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] ⠶ is used for both opening and closing parentheses.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Its placement relative to spaces and other characters determines its interpretation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Punctuation varies from language to language.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, French Braille uses ⠢ for its question mark and swaps the quotation marks and parentheses (to ⠶ and ⠦⠴); it uses (⠲) for both the period and the decimal point, and the English decimal point (⠨) to mark capitalization.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille contractions are words and affixes that are shortened so that they take up fewer cells.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In English Braille, for example, the word *afternoon* is written with just three letters, ⠁⠋⠝ ⟨afn⟩, much like stenoscript.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] There are also several abbreviation marks that create what are effectively logograms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The most common of these is dot 5, which combines with the first letter of words.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] With the letter ⠍ *m*, the resulting word is ⠐⠍ *mother*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] There are also ligatures ("contracted" letters), which are single letters in braille but correspond to more than one letter in print.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The letter ⠯ *and*, for example, is used to write words with the sequence *a-n-d* in them, such as ⠛⠗⠯ *grand*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Most braille embossers support between 34 and 40 cells per line, and 25 lines per page.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A manually operated Perkins braille typewriter supports a maximum of 42 cells per line (its margins are adjustable), and typical paper allows 25 lines per page.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A large interlining Stainsby has 36 cells per line and 18 lines per page.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] An A4-sized Marburg braille frame, which allows interpoint braille (dots on both sides of the page, offset so they do not interfere with each other), has 30 cells per line and 27 lines per page.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A Braille writing machine is a typewriter with six keys that allows the user to write braille on a regular hard copy page.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The first Braille typewriter to gain general acceptance was invented by Frank Haven Hall (Superintendent of the Illinois School for the Blind), and was presented to the public in 1892.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The Stainsby Brailler, developed by Henry Stainsby in 1903, is a mechanical writer with a sliding carriage that moves over an aluminium plate as it embosses Braille characters.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] An improved version was introduced around 1933.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1951 David Abraham, a woodworking teacher at the Perkins School for the Blind, produced a more advanced Braille typewriter, the Perkins Brailler.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille printers or embossers were produced in the 1950s.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1960 Robert Mann, a teacher in MIT, wrote DOTSYS, a software that allowed automatic braille translation, and another group created an embossing device called "M.I.T.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The Mitre Corporation team of Robert Gildea, Jonathan Millen, Reid Gerhart and Joseph Sullivan (now president of Duxbury Systems) developed DOTSYS III, the first braille translator written in a portable programming language.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] DOTSYS III was developed for the Atlanta Public Schools as a public domain program.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1991 Ernest Bate developed the Mountbatten Brailler, an electronic machine used to type braille on braille paper, giving it a number of additional features such as word processing, audio feedback and embossing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] This version was improved in 2008 with a quiet writer that had an erase key.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Morgan produced the first SMART Brailler machine, with added text to speech function and allowed digital capture of data entered.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille is traditionally read in hardcopy form, such as with paper books written in braille, documents produced in paper braille (such as restaurant menus), and braille labels or public signage.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] It can also be read on a refreshable braille display either as a stand-alone electronic device or connected to a computer or smartphone.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Refreshable braille displays convert what is visually shown on a computer or smartphone screen into braille through a series of pins that rise and fall to form braille symbols.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Currently more than 1% of all printed books have been translated into hardcopy braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The fastest braille readers apply a light touch and read braille with two hands, although reading braille with one hand is also possible.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Although the finger can read only one braille character at a time, the brain chunks braille at a higher level, processing words a digraph, root or suffix at a time.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Neuroimaging research has shown that, in people blinded early in life, tactile discrimination during braille reading can activate cortical areas normally associated with vision, including the primary and secondary visual cortex.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] There are many different styles and techniques used for the understanding and development of braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Holland suggests that there is no specific technique that is superior to any other.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Since braille is one of the few writing systems where tactile perception, as opposed to visual perception, is used a braille reader must develop new skills, such as the ability to create smooth and even pressures when running one's fingers along the words.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Another study by Lowenfield and Abel shows that braille can be read "the fastest and best... by students who read using the index fingers of both hands".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Another reading skill is to finish reading the end of a line with the right hand and to find the beginning of the next line with the left hand simultaneously.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Children who are blind miss out on fundamental parts of early and advanced education if not provided with the necessary tools, such as access to educational materials in braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Children who are blind or visually impaired can begin learning foundational braille skills from a very young age to become fluent braille readers as they get older.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Sighted children are naturally exposed to written language on signs, on TV and in the books they see.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Blind children require the same early exposure to literacy, through access to braille rich environments and opportunities to explore the world around them.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Print-braille books, for example, present text in both print and braille and can be read by sighted parents to blind children (and vice versa), allowing blind children to develop an early love for reading even before formal reading instruction begins.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Adults who experience sight loss later in life or who did not have the opportunity to learn it when they were younger can also learn braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In most cases, adults who learn braille were already literate in print before vision loss and so instruction focuses more on developing the tactile and motor skills needed to read braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] While different countries publish statistics on how many readers in a given organization request braille, these numbers only provide a partial picture of braille literacy statistics.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, this data does not survey the entire population of braille readers or always include readers who are no longer in the school system (adults) or readers who request electronic braille materials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Therefore, there are currently no reliable statistics on braille literacy rates, as described in a publication in the *Journal of Visual Impairment and Blindness*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Regardless of the precise percentage of braille readers, there is consensus that braille should be provided to all those who benefit from it.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Numerous factors influence access to braille literacy, including school budget constraints, technology advancements such as screen-reader software, access to qualified instruction, and different philosophical views over how blind children should be educated.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the US, a key turning point for braille literacy was the passage of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, an act of Congress that moved thousands of children from specialized schools for the blind into mainstream public schools.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Because only a small percentage of public schools could afford to train and hire braille-qualified teachers, braille literacy has declined since the law took effect.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille literacy rates have improved slightly since the bill was passed, in part because of pressure from consumers and advocacy groups that has led 27 states to pass legislation mandating that children who are legally blind be given the opportunity to learn braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1998 there were 57,425 legally blind students registered in the United States, but only 10% (5,461) of them used braille as their primary reading medium.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Early braille education is crucial to literacy for a blind or low-vision child.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] A study conducted in the state of Washington found that people who learned braille at an early age did just as well as, if not better than, their sighted peers in several areas, including vocabulary and comprehension.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the preliminary adult study, while evaluating the correlation between adult literacy skills and employment, it was found that 44% of the participants who had learned to read in braille were unemployed, compared to the 77% unemployment rate of those who had learned to read using print.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Currently, among the estimated 85,000 blind adults in the United States, 90% of those who are braille-literate are employed.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Among adults who do not know braille, only 33% are employed.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Statistically, history has proven that braille reading proficiency provides an essential skill set that allows blind or low-vision children to compete with their sighted peers in a school environment and later in life as they enter the workforce.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Regardless of the specific percentage of braille readers, proponents point out the importance of increasing access to braille for all those who can benefit from it.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille characters are much larger than their printed equivalents, and the standard 11 by 11+1⁄2 in (28 by 29 cm) page has room for only 25 lines of 43 characters.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] To reduce space and increase reading speed, most braille alphabets and orthographies use ligatures, abbreviations, and contractions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Virtually all English braille books in hardcopy (paper) format are transcribed in contracted braille: The Library of Congress's *Instruction Manual for Braille Transcribing* runs to over 300 pages, and braille transcribers must pass certification tests.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Uncontracted braille was previously known as grade 1 braille, and contracted braille was previously known as grade 2 braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Uncontracted braille is a direct transliteration of print words (one-to-one correspondence); hence, the word "about" would contain all the same letters in uncontracted braille as it does in inkprint.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Contracted braille includes short forms to save space; hence, for example, the letters "ab" when standing alone represent the word "about" in English contracted braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In English, some braille users only learn uncontracted braille, particularly if braille is being used for shorter reading tasks such as reading household labels.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] However, those who plan to use braille for educational and employment purposes and longer reading texts often go on to contracted braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The system of contractions in English Braille begins with a set of 23 words contracted to single characters.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Thus the word *but* is contracted to the single letter *b*, *can* to *c*, *do* to *d*, and so on.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Even this simple rule creates issues requiring special cases; for example, *d* is, specifically, an abbreviation of the verb *do*; the noun *do* representing the note of the musical scale is a different word and must be spelled out.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Portions of words may be contracted, and many rules govern this process.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, the character with dots 2-3-5 (the letter "f" lowered in the Braille cell) stands for "ff" when used in the middle of a word.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] At the beginning of a word, this same character stands for the word "to"; the character is written in braille with no space following it.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] (This contraction was removed in the Unified English Braille Code.) At the end of a word, the same character represents an exclamation point.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Some contractions are more similar than their print equivalents.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For example, the contraction ⟨lr⟩, meaning "letter", differs from ⟨ll⟩, meaning "little", only by one dot in the second letter: ⠇⠇ *little*, ⠇⠗ *letter*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] This causes greater confusion between the braille spellings of these words and can hinder the learning process of contracted braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The contraction rules take into account the linguistic structure of the word; thus, contractions are generally not to be used when their use would alter the usual braille form of a base word to which a prefix or suffix has been added.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Some portions of the transcription rules are not fully codified and rely on the judgment of the transcriber.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Thus, when the contraction rules permit the same word in more than one way, preference is given to "the contraction that more nearly approximates correct pronunciation".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] "Grade 3 braille" is a variety of non-standardized systems that include many additional shorthand-like contractions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] They are not used for publication, but by individuals for their personal convenience.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] When people produce braille, this is called braille transcription.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] When computer software produces braille, this is called a braille translator.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille translation software exists to handle almost all of the common languages of the world, and many technical areas, such as mathematics (mathematical notation), for example WIMATS, music (musical notation), and tactile graphics.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Consequently, mutual intelligibility was greatly hindered by this state of affairs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 1878, the International Congress on Work for the Blind, held in Paris, proposed an international braille standard, where braille codes for different languages and scripts would be based, not on the order of a particular alphabet, but on phonetic correspondence and transliteration to Latin.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] This unified braille has been applied to the languages of India and Africa, Arabic, Vietnamese, Hebrew, Russian, and Armenian, as well as nearly all Latin-script languages.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Other systems for assigning values to braille patterns are also followed beside the simple mapping of the alphabetical order onto the original French order.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Some braille alphabets start with unified braille, and then diverge significantly based on the phonology of the target languages, while others diverge even further.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the various Chinese systems, traditional braille values are used for initial consonants and the simple vowels.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In both Mandarin and Cantonese Braille, however, characters have different readings depending on whether they are placed in syllable-initial (onset) or syllable-final (rime) position.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] For instance, the cell for Latin *k*, ⠅, represents Cantonese *k* (*g* in Yale and other modern romanizations) when initial, but *aak* when final, while Latin *j*, ⠚, represents Cantonese initial *j* but final *oei*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Novel systems of braille mapping include Korean, which adopts separate syllable-initial and syllable-final forms for its consonants, explicitly grouping braille cells into syllabic groups in the same way as hangul.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Japanese, meanwhile, combines independent vowel dot patterns and modifier consonant dot patterns into a single braille cell – an abugida representation of each Japanese mora.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille is read by people who are blind, deafblind or who have low vision, and by both those born with a visual impairment and those who experience sight loss later in life.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille may also be used by print impaired people, who although may be fully sighted, due to a physical disability are unable to read print.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Even individuals with low vision will find that they benefit from braille, depending on level of vision or context (for example, when lighting or colour contrast is poor).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Braille is used for both short and long reading tasks.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Examples of short reading tasks include braille labels for identifying household items (or cards in a wallet), reading elevator buttons, accessing phone numbers, recipes, grocery lists and other personal notes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Examples of longer reading tasks include using braille to access educational materials, novels and magazines.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] People with access to a refreshable braille display can also use braille for reading email and ebooks, browsing the internet and accessing other electronic documents.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] It is also possible to adapt or purchase playing cards and board games in braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In India there are instances where the parliament acts have been published in braille, such as *The Right to Information Act*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Sylheti Braille is used in Northeast India.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In Canada, passenger safety information in braille and tactile seat row markers are required aboard planes, trains, large ferries, and interprovincial busses pursuant to the Canadian Transportation Agency's regulations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the United States, the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990 requires various building signage to be in braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the United Kingdom, medicines are required to have the name of the medicine in Braille on the labeling.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The current series of Canadian banknotes has a tactile feature consisting of raised dots that indicate the denomination, allowing bills to be easily identified by blind or low vision people.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] It does not use standard braille numbers to identify the value.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Instead, the number of full braille cells, which can be simply counted by both braille readers and non-braille readers alike, is an indicator of the value of the bill.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Mexican bank notes, Australian bank notes, Indian rupee notes, Israeli new shekel notes and Russian ruble notes also have special raised symbols to make them identifiable by persons who are blind or have low vision.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Euro coins were designed in cooperation with organisations representing blind people, and as a result they incorporate many features allowing them to be distinguished by touch alone.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In addition, their visual appearance is designed to make them easy to tell apart for persons who cannot read the inscriptions on the coins.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] "A good design for the blind and partially sighted is a good design for everybody" was the principle behind the cooperation of the European Central Bank and the European Blind Union during the design phase of the first series euro banknotes in the 1990s.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] As a result, the design of the first euro banknotes included several characteristics which aid both the blind and partially sighted to confidently use the notes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Australia introduced the tactile feature onto their five-dollar banknote in 2016.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the United Kingdom, the front of the £10 polymer note (the side with raised print), has two clusters of raised dots in the top left hand corner, and the £20 note has three.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] This tactile feature helps blind and partially sighted people identify the value of the note.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In 2003 the US Mint introduced the commemorative Alabama State Quarter, which recognized State Daughter Helen Keller on the Obverse, including the name Helen Keller in both English script and Braille inscription.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] This appears to be the first known use of braille on US Coin Currency, though not standard on all coins of this type.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The Braille set was added to the Unicode Standard in version 3.0 (1999).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Most braille embossers and refreshable braille displays do not use the Unicode code points, but instead reuse the 8-bit code points that are assigned to standard ASCII for braille ASCII.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] (Thus, for simple material, the same bitstream may be interpreted equally as visual letter forms for sighted readers or their exact semantic equivalent in tactile patterns for blind readers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Some embossers have proprietary control codes for 8-dot braille or for full graphics mode, where dots may be placed anywhere on the page without leaving any space between braille cells so that continuous lines can be drawn in diagrams, but these are rarely used and are not standard.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The Unicode standard encodes 6-dot and 8-dot braille glyphs according to their binary appearance, rather than following their assigned numeric order.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Dot 1 corresponds to the least significant bit of the low byte of the Unicode scalar value, and dot 8 to the high bit of that byte.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The Unicode block for braille is U+2800 ...
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The mapping of patterns to characters etc. is language dependent: even for English for example, see American Braille and English Braille.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Every year on 4 January, World Braille Day is observed internationally to commemorate the birth of Louis Braille and to recognize his efforts.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] Although the event is not considered a public holiday, it has been recognized by the United Nations as an official day of celebration since 2019.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] The 200th anniversary of the launch of braille was celebrated in 2024.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] In the UK, the Royal National Institute of Blind People has held celebrations from September 2024 until August 2025.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/braille] There is a variety of contemporary electronic devices that serve the needs of blind people that operate in Braille, such as refreshable braille displays and braille e-books that use different technologies for transmitting graphic information of different types (pictures, maps, graphs, texts, etc.).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/brown-waste] Brown waste is considered the most environmentally friendly way to dispose of it in the ecosystem.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/brown-waste] Some companies use this waste to make artificial wood, and other products used for non-food grade materials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Plants of the genus *Arctium* have dark green leaves that can grow up to 70 centimetres (28 inches) long.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] They are generally large, coarse, and ovate, with the lower ones being heart-shaped.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] *Arctium* species generally flower from July through October.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock flowers provide essential pollen and nectar for honeybees around August, when clover is on the wane and before the goldenrod starts to bloom.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In 1753, the Swedish botanist Carl Linnaeus established genus *Arctium* by recognizing two species: *Arctium lappa* and *Arctium personata*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The type specimen *Arctium lappa* was collected from a cultivated waste area in Europe ("habitat in Europae cultis ruderatis").
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] As of August 2025, the name *Arctium personata* is a synonym for *Carduus personata*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] A large number of species have been placed in genus *Arctium* at one time or another, but most of them are now classified in the related genus *Cousinia*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The precise limits between *Arctium* and *Cousinia* are hard to define; there is an exact relation between their molecular phylogeny.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The burdocks are sometimes confused with the cockleburs (genus *Xanthium*) and rhubarb (genus *Rheum*).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Botanists disagree about the number of taxa introduced into North America but most authorities accept at least the following three species: *Arctium lappa*, *Arctium minus*, and *Arctium tomentosum*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The influential *Flora of North America* and others accept **only** those three species.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In addition to three species, some authorities accept one or more hybrids.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The United States Department of Agriculture accepts a fourth species, *Arctium vulgare*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Circa 16th century, from bur + dock, the latter meaning sorrel of the genus Rumex.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] All *Arctium* species are native to Europe and/or Asia but several species have been widely introduced.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In Eurasia, native *Arctium* species range from Greenland to Siberia in the north, and from Macaronesia to Peninsular Malaysia in the south.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The roots of burdock, among other plants, are eaten by the larva of the ghost moth (*Hepialus humuli*).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The plant is used as a food plant by other Lepidoptera including brown-tail, *Coleophora paripennella*, *Coleophora peribenanderi*, the Gothic, lime-speck pug and scalloped hazel.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The prickly heads of burdock (burs) are noted for easily catching on to fur and clothing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Thus the bur is an excellent mechanism for seed dispersal.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In England, some birdwatchers have reported that birds have become entangled in the burs leading to a slow death, as they are unable to free themselves.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The green, above-ground portions may cause contact dermatitis in individual with allergies as the plant contains lactones.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The taproot of young burdock plants can be harvested and eaten as a root vegetable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] While generally out of favour in modern European cuisine, it is popular in East Asia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] *Arctium lappa* is known as *niúbàng* (牛蒡) in Chinese, the same name having been borrowed into Japanese as *gobō*, and is eaten in Japan, Korea and Taiwan.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In Korean, burdock root is called *u-eong* (우엉) and sold as *tong u-eong* (통우엉), or "whole burdock".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Plants are cultivated for their slender roots, which can grow up to about one metre long and two centimetres across.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock root is very crisp and has a sweet, mild, or pungent flavour with a little muddy harshness that can be reduced by soaking julienned or shredded roots in water for five to ten minutes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The roots have been used as potato substitutes in Russia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Immature flower stalks may also be harvested in late spring, before flowers appear; their taste resembles that of artichoke, to which the burdock is related.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The stalks are thoroughly peeled, and either eaten raw, or boiled in salt water.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Leaves are also eaten in spring in Japan when a plant is young and leaves are soft.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Some *A. lappa* cultivars are specialized for this purpose.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] A popular Japanese dish is *kinpira gobō* (金平牛蒡), julienned or shredded burdock root and carrot, braised with soy sauce, sugar, mirin and/or sake, and sesame oil.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Another is burdock makizushi (sushi filled with pickled burdock root; the burdock root is often artificially coloured orange to resemble a carrot).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In the second half of the 20th century, burdock achieved international recognition for its culinary use due to the increasing popularity of the macrobiotic diet, which advocates its consumption.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] It contains a fair amount of dietary fiber (GDF, 6 g per 100 g), calcium, potassium, and amino acids, and is low in calories.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] It contains a polyphenol oxidase, which causes its darkened surface and muddy harshness by forming tannin-iron complexes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock root's harshness harmonizes well with pork in miso soup (tonjiru) and with Japanese-style pilaf (takikomi gohan).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Dandelion and burdock is a soft drink that has long been popular in the United Kingdom; it has its origins in hedgerow mead commonly drunk in the mediæval period.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock is believed to be a galactagogue, a substance that increases lactation, but it is sometimes recommended to be avoided during pregnancy based on animal studies that show components of burdock to cause uterus stimulation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In Europe, burdock root was used as a bittering agent in beer before the widespread adoption of hops for this purpose.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The seeds of *A. lappa* are used in traditional Chinese medicine under the name *niubangzi* (Chinese: 牛蒡子; pinyin: *niúbángzi*; some dictionaries list the Chinese as just Chinese: 牛蒡; pinyin: *niúbàng*).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock is a traditional medicinal herb used for many ailments.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock root oil extract, also called bur oil, is used in Europe as a scalp treatment.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In Turkish Anatolia, the burdock plant was believed to ward off the evil eye, and as such is often a motif appearing woven into kilims for protection.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] With its many flowers, the plant also symbolizes abundance.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Before and during World War II, Japanese soldiers were issued a 15-1/2-inch bayonet held in a black-painted scabbard, the juken.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Their nickname was the burdock sword (*gobo ken*).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Mary Palmer's mid 18th century *Devonshire Dialogue* records the burrs of the plant being known in Devon, England, as "bachelor's-buttons".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The English folk artist Nancy Kerr refers to "The Land of Santa Georgia where the Banks of Burdocks Grow" in her song Santa Georgia, supposedly representing the relationship between country and city in modern England (especially Sheffield).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Burdock Everdeen from the Hunger Games is named after this plant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] After taking his dog for a walk one day in the late 1940s (1948), George de Mestral, a Swiss inventor, became curious about the seeds of the burdock plant that had attached themselves to his clothes and to the dog's fur.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Under a microscope, he looked closely at the hook system that the seeds use to hitchhike on passing animals aiding seed dispersal, and he realized that the same approach could be used to join other things together.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] His work led to the development of the hook and loop fastener, which was initially sold under the Velcro brand name.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] Serbo-Croatian uses the same word, *čičak*, for burdock and velcro; Turkish does the same with the name *pitrak*, while in the Polish language *rzep* means both "burr" and "velcro".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] The German word for burdock is *Klette* and velcro is *Klettverschluss* (= burdock fastener).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/burdock] In Norwegian burdock is *borre* and velcro *borrelås*, which translates to "burdock lock".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The **calorie** is a unit of energy that originated from the caloric theory of heat.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The **small calorie** or **gram calorie** is defined as the amount of heat needed to raise the temperature of one milliliter of water by one degree Celsius (or one kelvin).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In the US, "large calorie" is also used to mean kilocalorie (1 kcal = 1000 cal) .
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In nutrition and food science, the term *calorie* and the symbol *cal* may refer to the large unit or to the small unit in different regions of the world.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] It is generally used in publications and package labels to express the energy value of foods in per serving or per weight, recommended dietary caloric intake, metabolic rates, etc.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] Some authors recommend the spelling *Calorie* and the symbol *Cal* (both with a capital C) if the large calorie is meant, to avoid confusion; however, this convention is often ignored.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In physics and chemistry, the word *calorie* and its symbol usually refer to the small unit, the large one being called *kilocalorie* (kcal).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] However, the calorie is not part of the International System of Units (SI) and is regarded as obsolete, having been replaced by the SI derived unit of energy, the joule (J), or the kilojoule (kJ) for 1,000 joules.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The precise equivalence between calories and joules has varied over the years, but in thermochemistry and nutrition it is now generally assumed that one (small) calorie (**thermochemical calorie**) is equal to exactly 4.184 J, and therefore one kilocalorie (one large calorie) is 4184 J or 4.184 kJ.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The term "calorie" comes from Latin *calor* 'heat'.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] It was first introduced by Nicolas Clément, as a unit of heat energy, in lectures on experimental calorimetry during the years 1819–1824.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The term (written with lowercase "c") entered French and English dictionaries between 1841 and 1867.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The same term was used for the "small" unit by Pierre Antoine Favre (chemist) and Jean Thiébault Silbermann (physicist) in 1852.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In 1879, Marcellin Berthelot distinguished between gram-calorie and kilogram-calorie, and proposed using "Calorie", with capital "C", for the large unit.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] This usage was adopted by Wilbur Olin Atwater, a professor at Wesleyan University, in 1887, in an influential article on the energy content of food.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The smaller unit was used by U.S. physician Joseph Howard Raymond, in his 1894 textbook *A Manual of Human Physiology*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] He proposed calling the "large" unit "kilocalorie", but the term did not catch on until some years later.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The small calorie (cal) was recognized as a unit of the CGS system in 1896, alongside the already-existing CGS unit of energy, the erg (first suggested by Clausius in 1864, under the name *ergon*, and officially adopted in 1882).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In 1928, there were already serious complaints about the possible confusion arising from the two main definitions of the calorie and whether the notion of using the capital letter to distinguish them was sound.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The joule was the officially adopted SI unit of energy at the ninth General Conference on Weights and Measures in 1948.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The calorie was mentioned in the 7th edition of the SI brochure as an example of a non-SI unit.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The alternate spelling calory is a less-common, non-standard variant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The "small" calorie is broadly defined as the amount of energy needed to increase the temperature of 1 gram of water by 1 °C (or 1 K, which is the same increment, a gradation of one percent of the interval between the melting point and the boiling point of water).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The actual amount of energy required to accomplish this temperature increase depends on the atmospheric pressure and the starting temperature; different choices of these parameters have resulted in several different precise definitions of the unit.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The standard atmospheric pressure can be taken to be 101.325 kPa.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The figure depends on the conversion factor between "international joules" and "absolute" (modern, SI) joules.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The two definitions most common in older literature appear to be the *15 °C calorie* and the *thermochemical calorie*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] Until 1948, the latter was defined as 4.1833 international joules; the current standard of 4.184 J was chosen to have the new thermochemical calorie represent the same quantity of energy as before.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In North America, in a nutritional context, the "large" unit is used almost exclusively.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] It is generally written "calorie" with lowercase "c" and symbol "cal", even in government publications.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The SI unit kilojoule (kJ) may be used instead, in legal or scientific contexts.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] Most American nutritionists prefer the unit kilocalorie to the unit kilojoules, whereas most physiologists prefer to use kilojoules.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In the majority of other countries, nutritionists prefer the kilojoule to the kilocalorie.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In Europe, on nutrition facts labels, energy is expressed in both kilojoules and kilocalories, abbreviated as "kJ" and "kcal" respectively.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The unit is most commonly used to express food energy, namely the specific energy (energy per mass) of metabolizing different types of food.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] For example, fat (triglyceride lipids) contains 9 kilocalories per gram (kcal/g), while carbohydrates (sugar and starch) and protein contain approximately 4 kcal/g.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] The "large" unit is also used to express recommended nutritional intake or consumption, as in "calories per day".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] Dieting is the practice of eating food in a regulated way to decrease, maintain, or increase body weight, or to prevent and treat diseases such as diabetes and obesity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] As weight loss depends on reducing caloric intake, different kinds of calorie-reduced diets have been shown to be generally effective.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] In other scientific contexts, the term "calorie" and the symbol "cal" almost always refers to the small unit; the "large" unit being generally called "kilocalorie" with symbol "kcal".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] It is mostly used to express the amount of energy released in a chemical reaction or phase change, typically per mole of substance, as in kilocalories per mole.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] It is also occasionally used to specify other energy quantities that relate to reaction energy, such as enthalpy of formation and the size of activation barriers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] However, it is increasingly being superseded by the SI unit, the joule (J); and metric multiples thereof, such as the kilojoule (kJ).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/calorie] However, this estimate assumes that the volumetric heat capacity of the solution is 1 kcal/(L⋅K), which is not exact even for pure water.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is the 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust, and the fourth most abundant element in the universe by mass after hydrogen, helium, and oxygen.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon's abundance, its unique diversity of organic compounds, and its unusual ability to form polymers at the temperatures commonly encountered on Earth, enables it to serve as the common element of all known life.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is the second most abundant element in the human body by mass (about 18.5%) after oxygen.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The atoms of carbon can bond together in diverse ways, resulting in various allotropes of carbon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Well-known allotropes include graphite, diamond, amorphous carbon, and fullerenes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The physical properties of carbon vary widely with the allotropic form.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] For example, graphite is opaque and black, while diamond is highly transparent.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Graphite is soft enough to form a streak on paper (hence its name, from the Greek verb "γράφειν" which means "to write"), while diamond is the hardest naturally occurring material known.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Graphite is a good electrical conductor while diamond has a low electrical conductivity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Under normal conditions, diamond, carbon nanotubes, and graphene have the highest thermal conductivities of all known materials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] All carbon allotropes are solids under normal conditions, with graphite being the most thermodynamically stable form at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] They are chemically resistant and require high temperature to react even with oxygen.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The most common oxidation state of carbon in inorganic compounds is +4, while +2 is found in carbon monoxide and transition metal carbonyl complexes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The largest sources of inorganic carbon are limestones, dolomites and carbon dioxide, but significant quantities occur in organic deposits of coal, peat, oil, and methane clathrates.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon forms a vast number of compounds, with about two hundred million having been described and indexed; and yet that number is still only a fraction of the number of theoretically possible compounds under standard conditions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon in its solid state exists in several allotropes, including graphite, a soft, black, and slippery material, and diamond, the hardest naturally occurring substance.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This variation in physical properties arises from differences in atomic arrangement: graphite consists of layers of hexagonally arranged carbon atoms, while diamond features a rigid three-dimensional lattice.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Chemically, carbon is notable for its ability to form stable chemical bonds with many elements, particularly with other carbon atoms, and is capable of forming multiple stable covalent bonds with suitable multivalent atoms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is a component element in the large majority of all chemical compounds, with about two hundred million examples having been described in the published chemical literature.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon also has the highest sublimation point of all elements.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Compared to its well-known solid allotropes, the liquid and gaseous phases of carbon are far less studied.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In the vapor phase, some of the carbon is in the form of highly reactive diatomic carbon (also known as dicarbon, with a chemical formula of C2).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The liquid phase of carbon is a dark, mobile, and reflective liquid that can only exist above 4,000 K (3,730 °C; 6,740 °F) and under pressures exceeding 100 atmospheres.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is the sixth element, with a ground-state electron configuration of 1s22s22p2, of which the four outer electrons are valence electrons.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Its first four ionisation energies, 1086.5, 2352.6, 4620.5 and 6222.7 kJ/mol, are much higher than those of the heavier group-14 elements.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The electronegativity of carbon is 2.5, significantly higher than the heavier group-14 elements (1.8–1.9), but close to most of the nearby nonmetals, as well as some of the second- and third-row transition metals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon's covalent radii are normally taken as 77.2 pm (C−C), 66.7 pm (C=C) and 60.3 pm (C≡C), although these may vary depending on coordination number and what the carbon is bonded to.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In general, covalent radius decreases with lower coordination number and higher bond order.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Graphite is much more reactive than diamond at standard conditions, despite being more thermodynamically stable, as its delocalised pi system is much more vulnerable to attack.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] For example, graphite can be oxidised by hot concentrated nitric acid at standard conditions to mellitic acid, C6(CO2H)6, which preserves the hexagonal units of graphite while breaking up the larger structure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon-based compounds form the basis of all known life on Earth, and the carbon-nitrogen-oxygen cycle provides a small portion of the energy produced by the Sun, and most of the energy in larger stars (e.g.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Although it forms an extraordinary variety of compounds, most forms of carbon are comparatively unreactive under normal conditions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] At standard temperature and pressure, it resists all but the strongest oxidizers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It does not react with sulfuric acid, hydrochloric acid, chlorine or any alkalis.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] At elevated temperatures, carbon reacts with oxygen to form carbon oxides and will rob oxygen from metal oxides to leave the elemental metal.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon combines with some metals at high temperatures to form metallic carbides, such as the iron carbide cementite in steel and tungsten carbide, widely used as an abrasive and for making hard tips for cutting tools.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Atomic carbon is a very short-lived species and, therefore, carbon is stabilized in various multi-atomic structures with diverse molecular configurations called allotropes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The three relatively well-known allotropes of carbon are amorphous carbon, graphite, and diamond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Once considered exotic, fullerenes are nowadays commonly synthesized and used in research; they include buckyballs, carbon nanotubes, carbon nanobuds and nanofibers.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Several other exotic allotropes have also been discovered, such as lonsdaleite, glassy carbon, carbon nanofoam and linear acetylenic carbon (carbyne).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Graphene is a two-dimensional sheet of carbon with the atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] As of 2009, graphene appears to be the strongest material ever tested.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The process of separating it from graphite will require some further technological development before it is economical for industrial processes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] If successful, graphene could be used in the construction of a space elevator.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It could also be used to safely store hydrogen for use in a hydrogen based engine in cars.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The amorphous form is an assortment of carbon atoms in a non-crystalline, irregular, glassy state, not held in a crystalline macrostructure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is present as a powder, and is the main constituent of substances such as charcoal, lampblack (soot), and activated carbon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] At normal pressures, carbon takes the form of graphite, in which each atom is bonded trigonally to three others in a plane composed of fused hexagonal rings, just like those in aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The resulting network is 2-dimensional, and the resulting flat sheets are stacked and loosely bonded through weak van der Waals forces.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This gives graphite its softness and its cleaving properties (the sheets slip easily past one another).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Because of the delocalization of one of the outer electrons of each atom to form a π-cloud, graphite conducts electricity, but only in the plane of each covalently bonded sheet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This results in a lower bulk electrical conductivity for carbon than for most metals.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The delocalization also accounts for the energetic stability of graphite over diamond at room temperature.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] At very high pressures, carbon forms the more compact allotrope, diamond, having nearly twice the density of graphite.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Here, each atom is bonded tetrahedrally to four others, forming a 3-dimensional network of puckered six-membered rings of atoms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamond has the same cubic structure as silicon and germanium, and because of the strength of the carbon-carbon bonds, it is the hardest naturally occurring substance measured by resistance to scratching.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Contrary to the popular belief that *"diamonds are forever"*, they are thermodynamically unstable (Δf*G*°(diamond, 298 K) = 2.9 kJ/mol) under normal conditions (298 K, 105 Pa) and should theoretically transform into graphite.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] But due to a high activation energy barrier, the transition into graphite is so slow at normal temperature that it is unnoticeable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] However, at very high temperatures diamond will turn into graphite, and diamonds can burn up in a house fire.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The bottom left corner of the phase diagram for carbon has not been scrutinized experimentally.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Under some conditions, carbon crystallizes as lonsdaleite, a hexagonal crystal lattice with all atoms covalently bonded and properties similar to those of diamond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Fullerenes are a synthetic crystalline formation with a graphite-like structure, but in place of flat hexagonal cells only, some of the cells of which fullerenes are formed may be pentagons, nonplanar hexagons, or even heptagons of carbon atoms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The sheets are thus warped into spheres, ellipses, or cylinders.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The properties of fullerenes (split into buckyballs, buckytubes, and nanobuds) have not yet been fully analyzed and represent an intense area of research in nanomaterials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The names *fullerene* and *buckyball* are given after Richard Buckminster Fuller, popularizer of geodesic domes, which resemble the structure of fullerenes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The buckyballs are fairly large molecules formed completely of carbon bonded trigonally, forming spheroids (the best-known and simplest is the soccerball-shaped C60 buckminsterfullerene).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon nanotubes (buckytubes) are structurally similar to buckyballs, except that each atom is bonded trigonally in a curved sheet that forms a hollow cylinder.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Nanobuds were first reported in 2007 and are hybrid buckytube/buckyball materials (buckyballs are covalently bonded to the outer wall of a nanotube) that combine the properties of both in a single structure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Of the other discovered allotropes, carbon nanofoam is a ferromagnetic allotrope discovered in 1997.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It consists of a low-density cluster-assembly of carbon atoms strung together in a loose three-dimensional web, in which the atoms are bonded trigonally in six- and seven-membered rings.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is among the lightest known solids, with a density of about 2 kg/m3.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Similarly, glassy carbon contains a high proportion of closed porosity, but contrary to normal graphite, the graphitic layers are not stacked like pages in a book, but have a more random arrangement.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Linear acetylenic carbon has the chemical structure −(C≡C)n− .
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon in this modification is linear with *sp* orbital hybridization, and is a polymer with alternating single and triple bonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This carbyne is of considerable interest to nanotechnology as its Young's modulus is 40 times that of the hardest known material – diamond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 2015, a team at the North Carolina State University announced the development of another allotrope they have dubbed Q-carbon, created by a high-energy low-duration laser pulse on amorphous carbon dust.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Q-carbon is reported to exhibit ferromagnetism, fluorescence, and a hardness superior to diamonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Isotopes of carbon are atomic nuclei that contain six protons plus a number of neutrons (varying from 2 to 16).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon has two stable, naturally occurring isotopes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The isotope carbon-12 (12C) forms 98.93% of the carbon on Earth, while carbon-13 (13C) forms the remaining 1.07%.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The concentration of 12C is further increased in biological materials because biochemical reactions discriminate against 13C.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 1961, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted the isotope carbon-12 as the basis for atomic weights.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Identification of carbon in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) experiments is done with the isotope 13C.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon-14 (14C) is a naturally occurring radioisotope, created in the upper atmosphere (lower stratosphere and upper troposphere) by interaction of nitrogen with cosmic rays.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is found in trace amounts on Earth of 1 part per trillion (0.0000000001%) or more, mostly confined to the atmosphere and superficial deposits, particularly of peat and other organic materials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This isotope decays by 0.158 MeV β− emission.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Because of its relatively short half-life of 5700±30 years, 14C is virtually absent in ancient rocks.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The amount of 14C in the atmosphere and in living organisms is almost constant, but decreases predictably in their bodies after death.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This principle is used in radiocarbon dating, invented in 1949, which has been used extensively to determine the age of carbonaceous materials with ages up to about 40,000 years.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] There are 15 known isotopes of carbon and the shortest-lived of these is 8C which decays through proton emission and has a half-life of 3.5×10−21 s.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The exotic 19C exhibits a nuclear halo, which means its radius is appreciably larger than would be expected if the nucleus were a sphere of constant density.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is the fourth most abundant chemical element in the observable universe by mass after hydrogen, helium, and oxygen.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Some meteorites contain microscopic diamonds that were formed when the Solar System was still a protoplanetary disk.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Microscopic diamonds may also be formed by the intense pressure and high temperature at the sites of meteorite impacts.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 2014 NASA announced a greatly upgraded database for tracking polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) in the universe.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] More than 20% of the carbon in the universe may be associated with PAHs, complex compounds of carbon and hydrogen without oxygen.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] These compounds figure in the PAH world hypothesis where they are hypothesized to have a role in abiogenesis and formation of life.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] PAHs seem to have been formed "a couple of billion years" after the Big Bang, are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It has been estimated that the solid earth as a whole contains 730 ppm of carbon, with 2000 ppm in the core and 120 ppm in the combined mantle and crust.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Since the mass of the earth is 5.972×1024 kg, this would imply 4360 million gigatonnes of carbon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This is much more than the amount of carbon in the oceans or atmosphere (below).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In combination with oxygen in carbon dioxide, carbon is found in the Earth's atmosphere (approximately 900 gigatonnes of carbon — each ppm corresponds to 2.13 Gt) and dissolved in all water bodies (approximately 36,000 gigatonnes of carbon).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon in the biosphere has been estimated at 550 gigatonnes but with a large uncertainty, due mostly to a huge uncertainty in the amount of terrestrial deep subsurface bacteria.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Hydrocarbons (such as coal, petroleum, and natural gas) contain carbon as well.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Coal "reserves" (not "resources") amount to around 900 gigatonnes with perhaps 18,000 Gt of resources.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Proven sources of natural gas are about 175×1012 cubic metres (containing about 105 gigatonnes of carbon), but studies estimate another 900×1012 cubic metres of "unconventional" deposits such as shale gas, representing about 540 gigatonnes of carbon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is also found in methane hydrates in polar regions and under the seas.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Various estimates put this carbon between 500, 2500, or 3,000 Gt.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] According to one source, in the period from 1751 to 2008 about 347 gigatonnes of carbon were released as carbon dioxide to the atmosphere from burning of fossil fuels.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Another source puts the amount added to the atmosphere for the period since 1750 at 879 Gt, and the total going to the atmosphere, sea, and land (such as peat bogs) at almost 2,000 Gt.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is a constituent (about 12% by mass) of the very large masses of carbonate rock (limestone, dolomite, marble, and others).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Coal is very rich in carbon (anthracite contains 92–98%) and is the largest commercial source of mineral carbon, accounting for 4,000 gigatonnes or 80% of fossil fuel.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] As for individual carbon allotropes, graphite is found in large quantities in China, Russia, Mexico, Canada, and India.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Natural diamonds occur in the rock kimberlite, found in ancient volcanic "necks", or "pipes".
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Most diamond deposits are in Africa, notably in South Africa, Namibia, Botswana, the Republic of the Congo, and Angola.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamond deposits have also been found in Arkansas, Canada, the Russian Arctic, Brazil, and in Northern and Western Australia.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamonds are found naturally, but about 90% of all industrial diamonds used in the U.S. are now manufactured.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon-14 is formed in upper layers of the troposphere and the stratosphere at altitudes of 9–15 km by a reaction that is precipitated by cosmic rays.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Thermal neutrons are produced that collide with the nuclei of nitrogen-14, forming carbon-14 and a proton.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] As such, 1.5%×10−10 of atmospheric carbon dioxide contains carbon-14.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon-rich asteroids are relatively preponderant in the outer parts of the asteroid belt in the Solar System.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] These asteroids have not yet been directly sampled by scientists.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The asteroids can be used in hypothetical space-based carbon mining, which may be possible in the future, but is currently technologically impossible.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Formation of the carbon atomic nucleus occurs within a giant or supergiant star through the triple-alpha process.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The triple-alpha process happens in conditions of temperatures over 100 megakelvins and helium concentration that the rapid expansion and cooling of the early universe prohibited, and therefore no significant carbon was created during the Big Bang.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] According to current physical cosmology theory, carbon is formed in the interiors of stars on the horizontal branch.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] When massive stars die as supernova, the carbon is scattered into space as dust.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This dust becomes component material for the formation of the next-generation star systems with accreted planets.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The Solar System is one such star system with an abundance of carbon, enabling the existence of life as we know it.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is the opinion of most scholars that all the carbon in the Solar System and the Milky Way comes from dying stars.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The CNO cycle is an additional hydrogen fusion mechanism that powers stars, wherein carbon operates as a catalyst.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Rotational transitions of various isotopic forms of carbon monoxide (for example, 12CO, 13CO, and 18CO) are detectable in the submillimeter wavelength range, and are used in the study of newly forming stars in molecular clouds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Under terrestrial conditions, conversion of one element to another is very rare.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Therefore, the amount of carbon on Earth is effectively constant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Thus, processes that use carbon must obtain it from somewhere and dispose of it somewhere else.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The paths of carbon in the environment form the carbon cycle.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] For example, photosynthetic plants draw carbon dioxide from the atmosphere (or seawater) and build it into biomass, as in the Calvin cycle, a process of carbon fixation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Some of this biomass is eaten by animals, while some carbon is exhaled by animals as carbon dioxide.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The carbon cycle is considerably more complicated than this short loop; for example, some carbon dioxide is dissolved in the oceans; if bacteria do not consume it, dead plant or animal matter may become petroleum or coal, which releases carbon when burned.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon can form very long chains of interconnecting carbon–carbon bonds, a property that is called catenation.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon-carbon bonds are strong and stable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Through catenation, carbon forms a countless number of compounds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] A tally of unique compounds shows that more contain carbon than do not.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The simplest form of an organic molecule is the hydrocarbon—a large family of organic molecules that are composed of hydrogen atoms bonded to a chain of carbon atoms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] A hydrocarbon backbone can be substituted by other atoms, known as heteroatoms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Common heteroatoms that appear in organic compounds include oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, phosphorus, and the nonradioactive halogens, as well as the metals lithium and magnesium.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Organic compounds containing bonds to metal are known as organometallic compounds (*see below*).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Certain groupings of atoms, often including heteroatoms, recur in large numbers of organic compounds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] These collections, known as *functional groups*, confer common reactivity patterns and allow for the systematic study and categorization of organic compounds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Chain length, shape and functional groups all affect the properties of organic molecules.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In most stable compounds of carbon (and nearly all stable *organic* compounds), carbon obeys the octet rule and is *tetravalent*, meaning that a carbon atom forms a total of four covalent bonds (which may include double and triple bonds).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon occurs in all known organic life and is the basis of organic chemistry.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] When united with hydrogen, it forms various hydrocarbons that are important to industry as refrigerants, lubricants, solvents, as chemical feedstock for the manufacture of plastics and petrochemicals, and as fossil fuels.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] When combined with oxygen and hydrogen, carbon can form many groups of important biological compounds including sugars, lignans, chitins, alcohols, fats, aromatic esters, carotenoids and terpenes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] With nitrogen, it forms alkaloids, and with the addition of sulfur also it forms antibiotics, amino acids, and rubber products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] With the addition of phosphorus to these other elements, it forms DNA and RNA, the chemical-code carriers of life, and adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the most important energy-transfer molecule in all living cells.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Norman Horowitz, head of the Mariner and Viking missions to Mars (1965–1976), considered that the unique characteristics of carbon made it unlikely that any other element could replace carbon, even on another planet, to generate the biochemistry necessary for life.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Among these are the simple oxides of carbon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The most prominent oxide is carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This was once the principal constituent of the paleoatmosphere, but is a minor component of the Earth's atmosphere today.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Dissolved in water, it forms carbonic acid (H 2CO 3), but as most compounds with multiple single-bonded oxygens on a single carbon it is unstable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Through this intermediate, though, resonance-stabilized carbonate ions are produced.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Some important minerals are carbonates, notably calcite.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The other common oxide is carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is formed by incomplete combustion, and is a colorless, odorless gas.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The molecules each contain a triple bond and are fairly polar, resulting in a tendency to bind permanently to hemoglobin molecules, displacing oxygen, which has a lower binding affinity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Cyanide (CN−) has a similar structure, but behaves much like a halide ion (pseudohalogen).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] For example, it can form the nitride cyanogen molecule ((CN)2), similar to diatomic halides.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Likewise, the heavier analog of cyanide, cyaphide (CP−), is also considered inorganic, though most simple derivatives are highly unstable.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Other uncommon oxides are carbon suboxide (C 3O 2), the unstable dicarbon monoxide (C2O), carbon trioxide (CO3), cyclopentanepentone (C5O5), cyclohexanehexone (C6O6), and mellitic anhydride (C12O9).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] However, mellitic anhydride is the triple acyl anhydride of mellitic acid; moreover, it contains a benzene ring.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Thus, many chemists consider it to be organic.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] With reactive metals, such as tungsten, carbon forms either carbides (C4−) or acetylides (C2− 2) to form alloys with high melting points.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] These anions are also associated with methane and acetylene, both very weak acids.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] With an electronegativity of 2.5, carbon prefers to form covalent bonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] A few carbides are covalent lattices, like carborundum (SiC), which resembles diamond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Nevertheless, even the most polar and salt-like of carbides are not completely ionic compounds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Organometallic compounds by definition contain at least one carbon-metal covalent bond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Many metal carbonyls and metal cyanides exist (for example, tetracarbonylnickel and potassium ferricyanide); some workers consider metal carbonyl and cyanide complexes without other carbon ligands to be purely inorganic, and not organometallic.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] However, most organometallic chemists consider metal complexes with any carbon ligand, even 'inorganic carbon' (e.g., carbonyls, cyanides, and certain types of carbides and acetylides) to be organometallic in nature.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Metal complexes containing organic ligands without a carbon-metal covalent bond (e.g., metal carboxylates) are termed *metalorganic* compounds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] While carbon is understood to strongly prefer formation of four covalent bonds, other exotic bonding schemes are also known.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carboranes are highly stable dodecahedral derivatives of the [B12H12]2- unit, with one BH replaced with a CH+.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Thus, the carbon is bonded to five boron atoms and one hydrogen atom.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The cation [(Ph3PAu)6C]2+ contains an octahedral carbon bound to six phosphine-gold fragments.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This phenomenon has been attributed to the aurophilicity of the gold ligands, which provide additional stabilization of an otherwise labile species.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In nature, the iron-molybdenum cofactor (FeMoco) responsible for microbial nitrogen fixation likewise has an octahedral carbon center (formally a carbide, C(-IV)) bonded to six iron atoms.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 2016, it was confirmed that, in line with earlier theoretical predictions, the hexamethylbenzene dication contains a carbon atom with six bonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] More specifically, the dication could be described structurally by the formulation [MeC(η5-C5Me5)]2+, making it an "organic metallocene" in which a MeC3+ fragment is bonded to a η5-C5Me5− fragment through all five of the carbons of the ring.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In the cases above, each of the bonds to carbon contain less than two formal electron pairs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Thus, the formal electron count of these species does not exceed an octet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] This makes them hypercoordinate but not hypervalent.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The English name *carbon* comes from the Latin *carbo* for coal and charcoal, whence also comes the French *charbon*, meaning charcoal.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In German, Dutch and Danish, the names for carbon are *Kohlenstoff*, *koolstof*, and *kulstof* respectively, all literally meaning coal-substance.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon was discovered in prehistory and was known in the forms of soot and charcoal to the earliest human civilizations.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamonds were known probably as early as 2500 BCE in China, while carbon in the form of charcoal was made by the same chemistry as it is today, by heating wood in a pyramid covered with clay to exclude air.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 1722, René Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur demonstrated that iron was transformed into steel through the absorption of some substance, now known to be carbon.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 1772, Antoine Lavoisier showed that diamonds are a form of carbon; when he burned samples of charcoal and diamond and found that neither produced any water and that both released the same amount of carbon dioxide per gram.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 1779, Carl Wilhelm Scheele showed that graphite, which had been thought of as a form of lead, was instead identical with charcoal but with a small admixture of iron, and that it gave "aerial acid" (his name for carbon dioxide) when oxidized with nitric acid.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 1786, the French scientists Claude Louis Berthollet, Gaspard Monge and C.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Vandermonde confirmed that graphite was mostly carbon by oxidizing it in oxygen in much the same way Lavoisier had done with diamond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Some iron again was left, which the French scientists thought was necessary to the graphite structure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In their publication they proposed the name *carbone* (Latin *carbonum*) for the element in graphite which was given off as a gas upon burning graphite.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Antoine Lavoisier then listed carbon as an element in his 1789 textbook.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] A new allotrope of carbon, fullerene, that was discovered in 1985 includes nanostructured forms such as buckyballs and nanotubes.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Their discoverers – Robert Curl, Harold Kroto, and Richard Smalley – received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1996.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The resulting renewed interest in new forms led to the discovery of further exotic allotropes, including glassy carbon, and the realization that "amorphous carbon" is not strictly amorphous.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Commercially viable natural deposits of graphite occur in many parts of the world, but the most important sources economically are in China, India, Brazil, and North Korea.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Graphite deposits are of metamorphic origin, found in association with quartz, mica, and feldspars in schists, gneisses, and metamorphosed sandstones and limestone as lenses or veins, sometimes of a metre or more in thickness.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Deposits of graphite in Borrowdale, Cumberland, England were at first of sufficient size and purity that, until the 19th century, pencils were made by sawing blocks of natural graphite into strips before encasing the strips in wood.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Today, smaller deposits of graphite are obtained by crushing the parent rock and floating the lighter graphite out on water.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] There are three types of natural graphite—amorphous, flake or crystalline flake, and vein or lump.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Amorphous graphite is the lowest quality and most abundant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Contrary to science, in industry "amorphous" refers to very small crystal size rather than complete lack of crystal structure.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Amorphous is used for lower value graphite products and is the lowest priced graphite.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Large amorphous graphite deposits are found in China, Europe, Mexico and the United States.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Flake graphite is less common and of higher quality than amorphous; it occurs as separate plates that crystallized in metamorphic rock.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Flake graphite can be four times the price of amorphous.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Good quality flakes can be processed into expandable graphite for many uses, such as flame retardants.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The foremost deposits are found in Austria, Brazil, Canada, China, Germany and Madagascar.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Vein or lump graphite is the rarest, most valuable, and highest quality type of natural graphite.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It occurs in veins along intrusive contacts in solid lumps, and it is only commercially mined in Sri Lanka.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] According to the USGS, world production of natural graphite was 1.1 million tonnes in 2010, to which China contributed 800,000 t, India 130,000 t, Brazil 76,000 t, North Korea 30,000 t and Canada 25,000 t.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] No natural graphite was reported mined in the United States, but 118,000 t of synthetic graphite with an estimated value of $998 million was produced in 2009.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The diamond supply chain is controlled by a limited number of powerful businesses, and is also highly concentrated in a small number of locations around the world (see figure).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Only a very small fraction of the diamond ore consists of actual diamonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The ore is crushed, during which care has to be taken in order to prevent larger diamonds from being destroyed in this process and subsequently the particles are sorted by density.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Today, diamonds are located in the diamond-rich density fraction with the help of X-ray fluorescence, after which the final sorting steps are done by hand.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Before the use of X-rays became commonplace, the separation was done with grease belts; diamonds have a stronger tendency to stick to grease than the other minerals in the ore.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Historically diamonds were known to be found only in alluvial deposits in southern India.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamond production of primary deposits (kimberlites and lamproites) only started in the 1870s after the discovery of the diamond fields in South Africa.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Production has increased over time and an accumulated total of over 4.5 billion carats have been mined since that date.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Most commercially viable diamond deposits were in Russia, Botswana, Australia and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] By 2005, Russia produced almost one-fifth of the global diamond output (mostly in Yakutia territory; for example, Mir pipe and Udachnaya pipe) but the Argyle mine in Australia became the single largest source, producing 14 million carats in 2018.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] New finds, the Canadian mines at Diavik and Ekati, are expected to become even more valuable owing to their production of gem quality stones.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In the United States, diamonds have been found in Arkansas, Colorado, and Montana.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In 2004, a startling discovery of a microscopic diamond in the United States led to the January 2008 bulk-sampling of kimberlite pipes in a remote part of Montana.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] While natural diamonds form over time deep within the Earth, synthetic diamonds are created in laboratories through a variety of methods.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The original method uses high pressure and high temperature (HPHT) and is still widely used because of its relatively low cost.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The process involves large presses that can weigh hundreds of tons to produce a pressure of 5 GPa (730,000 psi) at 1,500 °C (2,730 °F).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The second method, using chemical vapor deposition (CVD), creates a carbon plasma over a substrate onto which the carbon atoms deposit to form diamond.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Other methods include explosive formation (forming detonation nanodiamonds) and sonication of graphite solutions.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is essential to all known living systems, and without it life as we know it could not exist (see alternative biochemistry).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The major economic use of carbon other than food and wood is in the form of hydrocarbons, most notably the greenhouse gas and fossil fuel methane gas and crude oil (petroleum).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Crude oil is distilled in refineries by the petrochemical industry to produce gasoline, kerosene, and other products.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Cellulose is a natural, carbon-containing polymer produced by plants in the form of wood, cotton, linen, and hemp.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Cellulose is used primarily for maintaining structure in plants.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Commercially valuable carbon polymers of animal origin include wool, cashmere, and silk.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Plastics are made from synthetic carbon polymers, often with oxygen and nitrogen atoms included at regular intervals in the main polymer chain.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The raw materials for many of these synthetic substances come from crude oil and coal.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The uses of carbon and its compounds are extremely varied.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It can form alloys with iron, of which the most common is carbon steel.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Graphite is combined with clays to form the 'lead' used in pencils used for writing and drawing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is also used as a lubricant and a pigment, as a moulding material in glass manufacture, in electrodes for dry batteries and in electroplating and electroforming, in brushes for electric motors, and as a neutron moderator in nuclear reactors.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Charcoal is used as a drawing material in artwork, barbecue grilling, iron smelting, and in many other applications.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Wood, coal and oil are used as fuel for production of energy and heating.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Gem quality diamond is used in jewelry, and industrial diamonds are used in drilling, cutting and polishing tools for machining metals and stone.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon fiber, which is produced by pyrolyzing synthetic polyester fibers, is used to reinforce plastics, creating advanced, lightweight composite materials.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon fiber is made by pyrolysis of extruded and stretched filaments of polyacrylonitrile (PAN) and other organic substances.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The crystallographic structure and mechanical properties of the fiber depend on the type of starting material, and on the subsequent processing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon fibers made from PAN have structure resembling narrow filaments of graphite, but thermal processing may re-order the structure into a continuous rolled sheet.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The result is fibers with higher specific tensile strength than steel.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon black is used as the black pigment in printing ink, artist's oil paint, and water colours, carbon paper, automotive finishes, India ink and laser printer toner.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon black is also used as a filler in rubber products such as tyres and in plastic compounds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Activated charcoal is used as an absorbent and adsorbent in filter material in applications as diverse as gas masks, water purification, and kitchen extractor hoods, and in medicine to absorb toxins, poisons, or gases from the digestive system.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon is used in chemical reduction at high temperatures.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Coke is used to reduce iron ore into iron (smelting).
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Case hardening of steel is achieved by heating finished steel components in carbon powder.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbides of silicon, tungsten, boron, and titanium are among the hardest known materials, and are used as abrasives in cutting and grinding tools.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon compounds make up most of the materials used in clothing, such as natural and synthetic textiles and leather, and almost all of the interior surfaces in the built environment other than glass, stone, drywall, and metal.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The diamond industry falls into two categories: one dealing with gem-grade diamonds and the other, with industrial-grade diamonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] While a large trade in both types of diamonds exists, the two markets function dramatically differently.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Unlike precious metals such as gold or platinum, gem diamonds do not trade as a commodity.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] There is a substantial mark-up in the sale of diamonds, and there is not a very active market for resale of diamonds.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Industrial diamonds are valued mostly for their hardness and heat conductivity, with the gemological qualities of clarity and color being mostly irrelevant.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] About 80% of mined diamonds (equal to about 100 million carats or 20 tonnes annually) are unsuitable for use as gemstones and relegated for industrial use (known as *bort)*.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Synthetic diamonds, invented in the 1950s, found almost immediate industrial applications; 3 billion carats (600 tonnes) of synthetic diamond is produced annually.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The dominant industrial use of diamond is in cutting, drilling, grinding, and polishing.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Most of these applications do not require large diamonds; in fact, most diamonds of gem-quality except for their small size can be used industrially.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamonds are embedded in drill tips or saw blades, or ground into a powder for use in grinding and polishing applications.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Specialized applications include use in laboratories as containment for high-pressure experiments (see diamond anvil cell), high-performance bearings, and limited use in specialized windows.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] With the continuing advances in the production of synthetic diamonds, new applications are becoming feasible.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Garnering much excitement is the possible use of diamond as a semiconductor suitable for microchips, and because of its exceptional heat conductance property, as a heat sink in electronics.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Pure carbon has extremely low toxicity to humans and can be handled safely in the form of graphite or charcoal.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] It is resistant to dissolution or chemical attack, even in the acidic contents of the digestive tract.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Consequently, once it enters into the body's tissues it is likely to remain there indefinitely.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon black was probably one of the first pigments to be used for tattooing, and Ötzi the Iceman was found to have carbon tattoos that survived during his life and for 5200 years after his death.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Inhalation of coal dust or soot (carbon black) in large quantities can be dangerous, irritating lung tissues and causing the congestive lung disease, coalworker's pneumoconiosis.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Diamond dust used as an abrasive can be harmful if ingested or inhaled.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Microparticles of carbon are produced in diesel engine exhaust fumes, and may accumulate in the lungs.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] However, in these examples, the harm may result from contaminants (e.g., organic chemicals, heavy metals) rather than from the carbon itself.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Carbon may burn vigorously and brightly in the presence of air at high temperatures.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Large accumulations of coal, which have remained inert for hundreds of millions of years in the absence of oxygen, may spontaneously combust when exposed to air in coal mine waste tips, ship cargo holds and coal bunkers, and storage dumps.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] In nuclear applications where graphite is used as a neutron moderator, accumulation of Wigner energy followed by a sudden, spontaneous release may occur.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] Annealing to at least 250 °C can release the energy safely, although in the Windscale fire the procedure went wrong, causing other reactor materials to combust.
[src:biointensive-agriculture/carbon] The great variety of carbon compounds include such lethal poisons as tetrodotoxin, the lectin ricin from seeds of the castor oil plant *Ricinus communis*, cyanide (CN−), and carbon monoxide; and such essentials to life as glucose and protein.
